commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, UniCash starts populated with sample data.

However, once this data is cleared, there is no way to restore the
sample data apart from manually deleting the unicash.json storage
which would require the user to bypass the App and access its storage
files directly.

Let's fix this minor issue by allowing the user, and any possible
testers of the UniCash application to restore the UniCash to its
initial default state such that any data-modification actions or tests
can be conveniently reversed.

commitResults.messageBody: Add Reset Functionality to UniCash

Previously, each transaction would be appended to the bottom of the
transaction list panel, which would impede the user from getting
immediate response as to their input, as the TransactionListPanel does
not scroll automatically.

Rather than making the panel auto-scroll, let's reverse
the order of the list so that the user is always looking at the most
recent transaction.

Additionally, let's modify the CommandBox to span the whole Window
with a smaller font size so that it can accomodate a longer input
command.

uses the transactions' Amount for calculations.

Let's implement the `Transaction#getAmountAsDouble` method and add

commitResults.messageTitle: Add updateExpenseSummary to Model and ModelManager
commitResults.messageBody:
In order to interact with the UI, ModelManager needs an attribute
to allow the UI to directly get the required data for plotting the
pie chart.

Let's add an `expenseSummary` HashMap<String, Double> for this. The
`expenseSummary` hashmap maps the expense Category to a value, which
represents the total expense for that category. The
updateExpenseSummary method will update the `expenseSummary` hashmap
when there are changes in the transactions. This warrants the need
for other methods that directly modify the transactions in UniCash
to also be updated to call this method when they make changes in the
transactions. Unit tests that test the added methods have also been
added.

Note 1: `UniCash#getSumOfExpensePerCategory` is the method that
calculates the expenses per category, while
`Model#updateExpenseSummary` simply uses the result of the
calculations to update `expenseSummary`.
Note 2: The `AddTransactionCommandTest` has been modified because
the ModelStub class has to implement the
`Model#updateExpenseSummary` prototype.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove unused (commented out) code for tidiness
Update SummaryCommand#execute method to call `Model#updateExpenseCategory` method

commitResults.messageBody:
`SummaryWindow` is currently plotting fictional (hardcoded) pie
chart data. Thus, it is not plotting the true data in UniCash.

Let's link the `expenseSummary` attribute of UniCash to
`SummaryWindow`. Since `MainWindow` is the UiPart that links `Logic`
and `SummaryWindow` together, we first modify the `SummaryWindow`
constructor to take in a `HashMap<String, Double> expenseSummary`.
Then, within `MainWindow`, when constructing `SummaryWindow`, we
pass in the `expenseSummary` hash map as an input to link
`MainWindow` and `SummaryWindow`. Next, we link `expenseSummary` to
`MainWindow` by creating the `getExpenseSummary` method in `Logic`
and `LogicManager`. Lastly, we edit `SummaryWindow#setPieChart` to
modify the pie chart's data using `expenseSummary`, instead of the
fictional (hardcoded) data.

Note 1: `MainWindow#handleSummary` now calls
`SummaryWindow#setPieChart` so that when the user executes the
"summary" command, the pie chart will be updated accordingly.
Note 2: The current implementation uses for-loops extensively. This
will later be modified to use Java streams instead.

Fix scrambled pie chart label bug
commitResults.messageBody:
When the user closes the pie chart and opens it again using the
"summary" command, the labels of the pie chart are scrambled up.

Let's fix this bug by calling the `VBox#layout` method after adding
the pie chart data.

Note: This solution was suggested here:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49843498/java9-bug-in-javafx-piechart-labels

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify `SummaryWindow.fxml` to remove animations and disable resize
commitResults.messageBody:
The pie chart's animations plays every time the user runs a command,
which might be distracting. Also, resizing the summary window may
cause the plot and words to be displayed strangely.

Let's disable window-resizing and animations to fix these issues.

`SummaryWindow#setPieChart` now does not take in any parameters. It
is able to directly access `UniCash#expenseSummary`. It may be
better to restrict `SummaryWindow`'s access to `expenseSummary`.

Let's modify `SummaryWindow#setPieChart` to take in `expenseSummary`
as a parameter instead. `MainWindow`'s initialization of
`SummaryWindow` also has to be updated due to `SummaryWindow`'s
constructor changing.

commitResults.messageBody: Update DG with Edit Transaction command
Add Summary Statistics Feature

`ModelManager` now has an `expenseSummary` attribute which stores the
updated `expenseSummary` calculated by `UniCash`. Having this variable
is not needed, and only increases the book-keeping we have to do to make
sure that `expenseSummary` is updated with every new command executed.
Instead, we can get the updated `expenseSummary` simply by making
`ModelManager` call `UniCash#getSumOfExpensePerCategory` if it needs the
updated `expenseSummary`.

Let's remove the `expenseSummary` attribute from `ModelManager` and
modify `Model#getExpenseSummary` to simply call
`UniCash#getSumOfExpensePerCategory`. Consequently, we will also not
need the `Model#updateExpenseSummary` method anymore as that method was
designed to update the `expenseSummary` attribute. Hence, let's also
remove that method from `Model`'s function prototypes. This also allows
us to remove `ModelStub#updateExpenseSummary` from the
`AddTransactionCommandTest.java` file.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add logic to calculate expense per year-month to Model component
commitResults.messageBody:
The current implementation does not support calculating the summary
statistics for the year-month level. This is needed for creating the
line chart in the summary window.

Let's add the `UniCash#getSumOfExpensePerYearMonth` to calculate the
total expense per year-month. The logic to filter away all income-type
transactions has also been extracted away to the `getAllExpense` method.
To make it more convenient to get the transaction's year-month value,
let's also make slight updates to the `DateTime` class from the `Model`
component. In particular, let's create a `DateTime#getYearMonth` method
that will return a `YearMonth` object.

The modifications made to `UniCash` have been made to shorten the code
for `UniCash#getSumOfExpensePerCategory`, which improves readability.
Furthermore, the logic to handle transactions with and without
categories has also been extracted to private methods also to improve
readability. Namely, these methods are `handleNoCategoryTransaction` and
`handleCategoryTransaction`.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add functionality to pass expense summary per year-month to `MainWindow`
commitResults.messageBody:
The expense summary per year-month is calculated by `UniCash` but is not
integrated with the rest of the other components.

Let's modify the `Logic` and `Model` components to pass the expense
summary from `UniCash` to `MainWindow` for displaying on the
`SummaryWindow`'s pop-up window.

Note: The design for the line graph in `SummaryWindow` has not been
completed as of this commit.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update `SummaryWindow` to add line chart and new icon for window
commitResults.messageBody:
The summary window now supports only the pie chart. It also uses the
help window's icon.

Let's integrate the line chart into the summary window, and add a new
icon for the window instead of using the help window's icon.

The window's icon should be changed because the help window's icon
contains a '?' symbol, which might confuse users.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify summary window's font styles to 'Inter' to follow other windows
Disable the summary window from opening if there are no expenses
commitResults.messageBody:
The summary window opens every time the user makes the "summary"
command. However, if there are no expenses to show, then there is no
reason to open the summary window.

Let's prevent the summary window from opening if there are no expenses.
However, if the summary window was already opened before, then this fix
will not close the summary window. It only applies if the summary window
was not opened before the "summary" command was made.

This was intentionally designed to behave this way because we do not
want to close the summary window when all expenses have been removed. If
we choose to do so, then it might confuse the user as the window might
suddenly disappear.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add newline to EOF of SummaryWindow.css
Modify SummaryWindow#fillExpenseSummary to return defensive copy
Remove unused variables and implement logging
Modify x-ticks of line chart to 'yyyy-MMM' format
Fix bug which causes summary window to resize on click
Modify sample data to have transactions spanning across multiple months
commitResults.messageBody:
The current sample data only contains transactions from 2023 Sep. This
causes the line chart plotted to only display transactions for one
month.

Let's modify the sample data to include transactions from more than one
month, and add multiple categories to some of the transactions.

This should be done because it showcases how the line chart looks like
in its usual state (i.e. having transactions from multiple months), and
how the pie chart will behave if there are transactions with multiple
categories.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify SummaryWindow.css to assign unique color to each pie
Update UG to contain Edit Transaction and Summary commands
Fix bug where `summary` output message is wrong when there is income
commitResults.messageBody:
There is a bug whereby the output message of the "summary" command
is "Opened UniCa$h summary window." even if there are no expenses,
but there are income transactions. This is caused by the
`SummaryCommand#execute` method implementation, which only checks if
there are transactions available, not if there are expense
transactions available.

Let's fix this bug by changing the check in `SummaryCommand#execute`
and instead, check if there are expense transactions available. To
do this, we create a new method in the Model class called
`hasExpenses`. This calls the new `UniCash#hasExpenses` method. We
also implement the `Model#hasExpenses` function prototype in the
other classes that implement the `Model` interface. Lastly, let's
add additional tests to bring maintain the current level of code
coverage.

Creating this new function prototype in `Model` allows minimal
modifications to the `SummaryCommand` class, as its `execute` method
only needs to call the `Model#hasExpenses` method. This maintains
readability of the `SummaryCommand#execute` method.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix bug where line chart time period is not 1 year ago to this month
commitResults.messageBody:
There is a bug where the line chart plots all expenses, even those
outside of the 1-year time period (i.e. 1 year ago to now). Also,
if there are no expenses, the line chart's default time period to
plot is 13 months ago to now.

Let's fix the first issue where all expenses are plotted
irregardless of their dates by adding the `filterExpenseSummary`
method, which removes the expenses outside of the 1 year range from
`expenseSummary`. Let's also fix the second issue where the default
time period is 13 months ago to now by fixing the
`EARLIEST_YEAR_MONTH` attribute from 1 year ago, to 11 months ago.
(if it is Nov 2023, the earliest year-month to plot should be Dec
2022, not Nov 2022). Since the preprocessing of `expenseSummary` now
consists of two steps (i.e. `fillExpenseSummary` and
`filterExpenseSummary`), let's also create a new method
`preprocessExpenseSummary` that simply performs the two steps.

Creating the additional `filterExpenseSummary` and
`preprocessExpenseSummary` is preferred over simply adding the
filter logic to `fillExpenseSummary` and changing the name of that
method. This is because according to the Single Responsibility
Principle, each method should only do one thing. Additionally,
combining all the code into one method will make the code less
readable.

Note: The areas of the code which used `YearMonth.now()` have also
been modified to use the `LATEST_YEAR_MONTH` attribute, which also
contains the same value as `YearMonth.now()`. This is done also to
improve readability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Implement requested fixes for summary feature

commitResults.messageBody:
Let's:
1. remove the getMessageFailure from "summary" CommandType as
it was pointed out that the event that the summary window does not
pop up is not a failure, but part of the feature's design.
2. replace the getMessageFailure message to a message constant in
`SummaryCommand` called `MESSAGE_NOT_SHOWING_SUMMARY`.
3. modify the output of calling `preprocessExpenseSummary` in
`SummaryWindow#setLineGraph` to be stored in another variable other
than `expenseSummary` to improve code quality.
4. fix typo errors in `MainWindow`.
